                     <h2>
                       APR-DRG </h2>
                        <p>
                            All Patient Refined DRG. Created by 3M. There are 315 base APR-DRG codes(Version 27.0). The 3M™ APR DRG Classification System (APR DRG) is a refinement of the AP-DRG grouper. (AP is All Patient; APR is All Patient Refined.) Like the AP-DRG grouper, it classifies inpatients into clinically similar groups based on ICD-9-CM and ICD-10-CM/PCS diagnosis and procedure codes and applies across the full spectrum of acute care patients. However, the APR DRG grouper includes many significant additions and modifications that extend its use beyond resource evaluation and payment. One critical enhancement is that APR DRGs divide each DRG into four subclasses for severity of illness (SOI) and four additional subclasses based on risk of mortality (ROM). Patients in each subclass of a particular APR DRG experience similar resource utilization and outcomes. This allows hospitals to use the group assignments for "apples-to-apples" comparisons of factors like length of stay (LOS), cost effectiveness, patient outcomes, individual physician performance, and variances from the norm. The APR DRG classification system serves as the basis of state-specific payment systems and hospital performance evaluations for many states.
                        </p>

                        <h3> Source </h3>

                        <p>
                            3MHIS
                        </p>

                        <p class="return-to-top">
                       <span class="clicktoup"> Return to Top </span></p>

                         <h2>
                       AP-DRG </h2>
                        <p>
                            All Patient DRG. All Patient Diagnosis Related Groups (AP-DRGs) are a modification of the original CMS Diagnosis Related Groups (DRGs). Like CMS DRGs, they are a set of inpatient classifications based on ICD-9-CM diagnosis and procedure codes, which relate a hospital’s case mix to resource demands and associated costs. However, AP-DRGs address the full spectrum of acute care patients rather than being limited to Medicare patients. To address the full range of patients, AP-DRGs include significantly modified classifications such as those for newborns, high risk pregnancies, transplants, HIV patients, tuberculosis patients, and substance abuse. In addition, AP-DRGs do not always use principal diagnosis as the initial variable in group assignment, and they incorporate a modified use of complications and comorbidities. AP-DRGs serve as the basis for state Medicaid payment systems in many all-payer states, such as New Jersey, Indiana, Massachusetts, and Washington state. 3M stopped development of AP-DRGs in January 2010, at v27.0, to focus on continued refinement of the APR DRG classification system.
                        </p>

                        <h3> Source </h3>

                        <p>
                            3MHIS
                        </p>

                        <p class="return-to-top">
                       <span class="clicktoup"> Return to Top </span></p>


