                     <h2>
                       ICD-9 Procedure </h2>
                       <h3>AKA: ICD9P</h3>
                        <p>
                            The Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) and the National Center for Health Statistics (NCHS), two departments within the U.S. Federal Government’s Department of Health and Human Services (DHHS) provide the following guidelines for coding and reporting using the International Classification of Diseases, 9th Revision, Clinical Modification (ICD-9-CM). These guidelines should be used as a companion document to the official version of the ICD-9-CM as published on CD-ROM by the U.S. Government Printing Office (GPO). These guidelines have been approved by the four organizations that make up the Cooperating Parties for the ICD-9-CM: the American Hospital Association (AHA), the American Health Information Management Association (AHIMA), CMS, and NCHS. These guidelines are included on the official government version of the ICD-9-CM, and also appear in  “Coding Clinic for ICD-9-CM” published by the AHA. ICD-9 Procedure codes are 3-4 characters in length. There are approximately 3,000 ICD-9 Procedure codes. On the UB-04, these are listed on FL 74, and on the CMS 1500, these are supplemented by CPT/HCPCS codes on FL 24D.
                       </p>

                        <h3> Source </h3>

                        <p>
                            CDC & AMA
                        </p>

                        <p class="return-to-top">
                       <span class="clicktoup"> Return to Top </span></p>
                                         
                     <h2>
                       ICD-9 Diagnosis </h2>
                       <h3>AKA: ICD9D</h3>
                        <p>
                            The Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) and the National Center for Health Statistics (NCHS), two departments within the U.S. Federal Government’s Department of Health and Human Services (DHHS) provide the following guidelines for coding and reporting using the International Classification of Diseases, 9th Revision, Clinical Modification (ICD-9-CM). These guidelines should be used as a companion document to the official version of the ICD-9-CM as published on CD-ROM by the U.S. Government Printing Office (GPO). These guidelines have been approved by the four organizations that make up the Cooperating Parties for the ICD-9-CM: the American Hospital Association (AHA), the American Health Information Management Association (AHIMA), CMS, and NCHS. These guidelines are included on the official government version of the ICD-9-CM, and also appear in  “Coding Clinic for ICD-9-CM” published by the AHA. ICD-9 Diagnosis codes are 3-5 characters in length. There are approximately 13,000 ICD-9 Diagnosis codes, and the first digit may be alpha(E or V) or numeric. Characters 2-5 are numeric. On the UB-04, these are listed on FL 66-67 and 69-70. On the CMS 1500, these are listed on FL 21 with a Designated indicator on FL 24E.
                        </p>

                        <h3> Source </h3>

                        <p>
                            CDC & AMA
                        </p>

                        <p class="return-to-top">
                       <span class="clicktoup"> Return to Top </span></p>

                    
